                But there are also many companies that started out like the rest, and haven't crashed. They found and fostered good traction.
            </p>
            <p class="text-l font-serif leading-relaxed text-gray-700 mb-4">
                But, they haven't reached the stars.
            </p>
            <p class="text-l font-serif leading-relaxed text-gray-700 mb-4">
                They have built a good business with somewhere between ~5 to 75 million in ARR. But they've hit a plateau or are about to.
            </p>
            <p class="text-l font-serif leading-relaxed text-gray-700 mb-4">
                They've probably got a lot of technical debt and product baggage. They're struggling to take advantage of their data. They're almost certainly having a hard time enabling their growth functions.
            </p>
            <p class="text-l font-serif leading-relaxed text-gray-700 mb-4">
                It's time to take a different approach - one focused on growing profitably and maximizing the enterprise value for a different but still good outcome.
            </p>
